folder: Roosevelt Avenue & Willets Point Boulevard, Queens, NY
original_title: Queens: Roosevelt Avenue - Willets Point Boulevard
text:
Roosevelt Avenue, south side at Willets Point Boulevard, from underneath the B. M. T. and I. R. T. subway "El," showing this area before it was improved to serve the millions of visitors who came to the 1939-40 New York World's Fair.
September 30, 1935
Views 1,2
P. L. Sperr

folder: Roosevelt Avenue & Willets Point Boulevard, Queens, NY
original_title: Queens: Roosevelt Avenue - Willets Point Boulevard
text:
Roosevelt Avenue, north side, at Willets Point Boulevard, viewing east and showing the Willets Point Boulevard station of the I. R. T. and B. M. T. subway systems. The area in the foreground was later improved as an auto parking space for visitors to the New York World's Fair of 1939-40.
October 18, 1936
Views 1,2
P. L. Sperr

folder: Roosevelt Avenue & Willets Point Boulevard, Queens, NY
original_title: Queens: Roosevelt Avenue - Willets Point Boulevard
text:
Roosevelt Avenue, south side, east from near Willets Point Boulevard, showing the I. R. T. and B. M. T. subway "El" on the former, running into Flushing across the Flushing River. This area was later improved to accommodate automobile visitors to the New York World's Fair 1939-40.
View 2 shows a more distant view of the "El" and the Flushing River bridge, seen from the Long Island Railroad tracks; view 3 shows a gas station near the Boulevard.
View 1: October 18, 1936
Views 2,3: Nay 30, 1938
P. L. Sperr

folder: Roosevelt Avenue & Willets Point Boulevard, Queens, NY
original_title: Queens: Roosevelt Avenue - Willets Point Boulevard
text:
Flushing Meadow Park (Queens): Viewing southeastward across the grounds of the World's Fair of 1939-40, seen from Roosevelt Avenue and Willets Point Boulevard. Clearly visible is the Trylon-the Fairs theme-- and some of the exhibition buildings under constraction.
View 2 shows the same area, in the Fair's second year of operation.
P.L. Sperr  View 1: May 30, 1938
NO REPRODUCTIONS  View 2: June 23, 1940
